questions.scenario:
You are debugging a production issue where migrating your Spring Boot 3.2 application to Java 21 Virtual Threads using `Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()` resulted in severe thread starvation and latency spikes under heavy database load. Thread dumps show that many virtual threads are in a state that blocks their carrier platform threads. Here is the offending code snippet:

java
public class QueryCoordinator {
    private final ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();

    public synchronized void processDataWithLegacyDriver(String Query) {
        // legacyDriver uses synchronized blocks internally for socket I/O
        legacyDriver.execute(Query);
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue where a write operation in a Spring `@Service` bean does not roll back when an asynchronous task fails. The log shows that the transaction commits successfully despite a `RuntimeException` being thrown inside the asynchronous block. Here is the code:

java
@Service
public class RegistrationService {
    @Autowired
    private UserRepository userRepository;

    @Transactional
    public void registerUser(User user) {
        userRepository.save(user);
        CompletableFuture.runAsync(() -> {
            throw new RuntimeException("Failed to send welcome pack");
        });
    }
}

You are debugging a production issue in a high-throughput Java gateway application. The gateway aggregates responses from multiple internal REST endpoints using `CompletableFuture`. Under sudden traffic spikes, the gateway's throughput drops to near zero and incoming requests start timing out. Thread dumps reveal that all threads in the application's default execution pool are blocked in the `WAITING` state. Here is the code structure used for aggregation:

java
public CompletableFuture<UserConfig> getUserConfig(String userId) {
    return CompletableFuture.supplyAsync(() -> {
        var profile = fetchProfile(userId).join(); // blocking join inside supplyAsync
        var preferences = fetchPreferences(userId).join(); // blocking join inside supplyAsync
        return new UserConfig(profile, preferences);
    });
}
